trans-unit.source: Scheduler High-Availability and Reliability
trans-unit.target: Scheduler High-Availability and Reliability

trans-unit.source: As a core Azure platform service, Azure Scheduler is highly available and features both geo-redundant service deployment and geo-regional job replication.
trans-unit.target: As a core Azure platform service, Azure Scheduler is highly available and features both geo-redundant service deployment and geo-regional job replication.

trans-unit.source: Azure Scheduler is available via the UI in almost every geo region that's in Azure today.
trans-unit.target: Azure Scheduler is available via the UI in almost every geo region that's in Azure today.

trans-unit.source: The list of regions that Azure Scheduler is available in is <linkText>listed here</linkText><title></title>.
trans-unit.target: The list of regions that Azure Scheduler is available in is <linkText>listed here</linkText><title></title>.

trans-unit.source: If a data center in a hosted region is rendered unavailable, the failover capabilities of Azure Scheduler are such that the service is available from another data center.
trans-unit.target: If a data center in a hosted region is rendered unavailable, the failover capabilities of Azure Scheduler are such that the service is available from another data center.

trans-unit.source: Not only is the Azure Scheduler front-end available for management requests, but your own job is also geo-replicated.
trans-unit.target: Not only is the Azure Scheduler front-end available for management requests, but your own job is also geo-replicated.

trans-unit.source: When there’s an outage in one region, Azure Scheduler fails over and ensures that the job is run from another data center in the paired geographic region.
trans-unit.target: When there’s an outage in one region, Azure Scheduler fails over and ensures that the job is run from another data center in the paired geographic region.

trans-unit.source: For example, if you’ve created a job in South Central US, Azure Scheduler automatically replicates that job in North Central US.
trans-unit.target: For example, if you’ve created a job in South Central US, Azure Scheduler automatically replicates that job in North Central US.

trans-unit.source: When there’s a failure in South Central US, Azure Scheduler ensures that the job is run from North Central US.
trans-unit.target: When there’s a failure in South Central US, Azure Scheduler ensures that the job is run from North Central US.

trans-unit.source: <linkText>The list of paired Azure regions is available here</linkText><title></title>.
trans-unit.target: <linkText>The list of paired Azure regions is available here</linkText><title></title>.

trans-unit.source: As a result, Azure Scheduler ensures that your data stays within the same broader geographic region in case of an Azure failure.
trans-unit.target: As a result, Azure Scheduler ensures that your data stays within the same broader geographic region in case of an Azure failure.

trans-unit.source: As a result, you need not duplicate your job just to add high availability – Azure Scheduler automatically provides high-availability capabilities for your jobs.
trans-unit.target: As a result, you need not duplicate your job just to add high availability – Azure Scheduler automatically provides high-availability capabilities for your jobs.

trans-unit.source: Azure Scheduler guarantees its own high-availability and takes a different approach to user-created jobs.
trans-unit.target: Azure Scheduler guarantees its own high-availability and takes a different approach to user-created jobs.

trans-unit.source: For example, your job may invoke an HTTP endpoint that’s unavailable.
trans-unit.target: For example, your job may invoke an HTTP endpoint that’s unavailable.

trans-unit.source: Azure Scheduler nonetheless tries to execute your job successfully, by giving you alternative options to deal with failure.
trans-unit.target: Azure Scheduler nonetheless tries to execute your job successfully, by giving you alternative options to deal with failure.

trans-unit.source: Azure Scheduler does this in two ways:
trans-unit.target: Azure Scheduler does this in two ways:

trans-unit.source: Azure Scheduler allows you to configure a retry policy.
trans-unit.target: Azure Scheduler allows you to configure a retry policy.

trans-unit.source: By default, if a job fails, Scheduler tries the job again four more times, at 30-second intervals.
trans-unit.target: By default, if a job fails, Scheduler tries the job again four more times, at 30-second intervals.

trans-unit.source: You may re-configure this retry policy to be more aggressive (for example, ten times, at 30-second intervals) or looser (for example, two times, at daily intervals.)
trans-unit.target: You may re-configure this retry policy to be more aggressive (for example, ten times, at 30-second intervals) or looser (for example, two times, at daily intervals.)

trans-unit.source: As an example of when this may help, you may create a job that runs once a week and invokes an HTTP endpoint.
trans-unit.target: As an example of when this may help, you may create a job that runs once a week and invokes an HTTP endpoint.

trans-unit.source: If the HTTP endpoint is down for a few hours when your job runs, you may not want to wait one more week for the job to run again since even the default retry policy will fail.
trans-unit.target: If the HTTP endpoint is down for a few hours when your job runs, you may not want to wait one more week for the job to run again since even the default retry policy will fail.

trans-unit.source: In such cases, you may reconfigure the standard retry policy to retry every three hours (for example) instead of every 30 seconds.
trans-unit.target: In such cases, you may reconfigure the standard retry policy to retry every three hours (for example) instead of every 30 seconds.

trans-unit.source: To learn how to configure a retry policy, refer to <linkText>retryPolicy</linkText><title></title>.
trans-unit.target: To learn how to configure a retry policy, refer to <linkText>retryPolicy</linkText><title></title>.

trans-unit.source: If the target endpoint for your Azure Scheduler job remains unreachable, Azure Scheduler falls back to the alternate error-handling endpoint after following its retry policy.
trans-unit.target: If the target endpoint for your Azure Scheduler job remains unreachable, Azure Scheduler falls back to the alternate error-handling endpoint after following its retry policy.

trans-unit.source: If an alternate error-handling endpoint is configured, Azure Scheduler invokes it.
trans-unit.target: If an alternate error-handling endpoint is configured, Azure Scheduler invokes it.

trans-unit.source: With an alternate endpoint, your own jobs are highly available in the face of failure.
trans-unit.target: With an alternate endpoint, your own jobs are highly available in the face of failure.

trans-unit.source: As an example, in the diagram below, Azure Scheduler follows its retry policy to hit a New York web service.
trans-unit.target: As an example, in the diagram below, Azure Scheduler follows its retry policy to hit a New York web service.

trans-unit.source: After the retries fail, it checks if there's an alternate.
trans-unit.target: After the retries fail, it checks if there's an alternate.

trans-unit.source: It then goes ahead and starts making requests to the alternate with the same retry policy.
trans-unit.target: It then goes ahead and starts making requests to the alternate with the same retry policy.

trans-unit.source: Note that the same retry policy applies to both the original action and the alternate error action.
trans-unit.target: Note that the same retry policy applies to both the original action and the alternate error action.

trans-unit.source: It’s also possible to have the alternate error action’s action type be different from the main action’s action type.
trans-unit.target: It’s also possible to have the alternate error action’s action type be different from the main action’s action type.

trans-unit.source: For example, while the main action may be invoking an HTTP endpoint, the error action may instead be a storage queue action that does error-logging.
trans-unit.target: For example, while the main action may be invoking an HTTP endpoint, the error action may instead be a storage queue action that does error-logging.

trans-unit.source: To learn how to configure an alternate endpoint, refer to <linkText>errorAction</linkText><title></title>.
trans-unit.target: To learn how to configure an alternate endpoint, refer to <linkText>errorAction</linkText><title></title>.
